---
description: Tailwind + visual design direction
globs:
  - "client/**/*.jsx"
  - "client/**/*.css"
alwaysApply: false
---
- Use Tailwind CSS utility classes as the primary styling approach — avoid
  inline styles and separate CSS files except for true one-offs.
- Pick a real design direction and stick to it: define a small token set
  (2-3 accent colors, one display font pairing, consistent spacing/radius
  scale) before building screens, then reuse it everywhere. No screen
  should introduce its own one-off palette.
- Avoid default AI-generated look-alikes: don't default to cream background
  + terracotta accent, or plain black + one neon accent, without a reason.
  Pick colors that suit a residential/community product — calm, trustworthy,
  legible — not a generic SaaS landing page palette.
- Respect roles visually too: a treasurer/admin dashboard can be denser and
  data-heavy; a resident's view (dues, complaints) should be simpler and
  mobile-first, since most residents will check this on their phone.
- Every screen: usable down to mobile width, visible focus states on
  interactive elements, no color-only status indicators (pair color with
  text/icon, e.g. "Paid" badge, not just green).
- Keep motion minimal and purposeful — a hover state or a subtle transition,
  not decorative animation everywhere.

  